article.description:
Rookie Seimone Augustus scored 21 points
and Minnesota beat the Charlotte Sting 70-62 Tuesday night in the
debut for Lynx interim coach Carolyn Jenkins.
article.headline: Augustus leads Lynx to W in Jenkins' coaching debut
article.linkText: Augustus leads Lynx to W in Jenkins' coaching debut
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Carolyn Jenkins didn't get nervous until
the end of her first game as Minnesota Lynx interim coach.

Rookie Seimone Augustus scored 21 points and the Lynx beat the
Charlotte Sting 70-62 Tuesday night in Jenkins' debut.

Amber Jacobs added 18 points, including the clinching free
throws with 21 seconds left, as the Lynx (9-15) won for only the
second time in 11 road games.

Jenkins, promoted from assistant coach on Sunday when Suzie
McConnell Serio resigned, didn't leave her seat much early in the
game as Augustus scored six points in an opening 11-0 run.

But Charlotte got within two in the fourth quarter, and Jenkins
started to feel the pressure of a head coach for the first time
since she was in charge at Sacramento State in 2003.

"When you're up 11-0 there's nothing to be nervous about,"
Jenkins said. "It's down the stretch when things are getting tight
that you have to make sure you're making the right decisions for
your team. Hopefully down the stretch we were able to do that."

Augustus helped put her coach at ease when she rebounded her own
miss and scored in the paint with 47 seconds left to give the Lynx
a 66-62 lead. Charlotte's LaToya Bond then missed consecutive
3-pointers before Jacobs' free throws.

"Losing a coach and everything, we just channeled our energy
elsewhere in trying to be a more motivated and confident team,"
said Augustus, the league's second-leading scorer. "We wanted to
get a road win."

Tammy Sutton-Brown tied a career high with 22 points and Kelly
Mazzante added 12 points and nine rebounds for the Sting (7-18),
who shot 27 percent in their second straight loss following a
four-game winning streak. The loss damaged the Sting's already dim
playoff hopes.

"That was a horrible effort," Sting coach Muggsy Bogues said.
"For us to be playing the way we have the past three weeks, and
knowing the importance of this game, that type of performance is
really frustrating.

"That team is going through a lot over there. We knew they
would come out and play with emotion. It's not like they came out
on fire. We allowed them to do whatever they wanted."

The Sting, who fell behind 44-31 early in the third quarter,
rallied by pounding the ball inside to Sutton-Brown, who also
scored 22 points in September 2004. She scored 11 points in the
period to get Charlotte within 56-52 entering the fourth quarter.
But the Sting, who were outrebounded 42-34, never led.

"We have to understand how important rebounding is at this
point of the season," Mazzante said. "We have nine games left and
we have to get it together."

Jenkins, who got more animated as the game wore on, had only one
assistant coach. Veteran Jim Lewis, the former head coach at
Fordham, was hired hours before the game.

"It's been emotional few days, but it's been great because the
players have been absolutely wonderful," Jenkins said. "I've just
been trying to support them and put them in a position to be
successful. They're still working hard."
